od already returned a task in step 3.) Instead, the string result is stored in the task that represents the completion of the method, `getStringTask`."},{"content":"The await operator retrieves the result from <ph id=\"ph1\">`getStringTask`</ph>.","pos":[11386,11447],"source":" The await operator retrieves the result from `getStringTask`."},{"content":"The assignment statement assigns the retrieved result to <ph id=\"ph1\">`urlContents`</ph>.","pos":[11448,11519],"source":" The assignment statement assigns the retrieved result to `urlContents`."},{"content":"When <ph id=\"ph1\">`AccessTheWebAsync`</ph> has the string result, the method can calculate the length of the string.","pos":[11529,11627],"source":"When `AccessTheWebAsync` has the string result, the method can calculate the length of the string."},{"content":"Then the work of <ph id=\"ph1\">`AccessTheWebAsync`</ph> is also complete, and the waiting event handler can resume.","pos":[11628,11724],"source":" Then the work of `AccessTheWebAsync` is also complete, and the waiting event handler can resume."},{"content":"In the full example at the end of the topic, you can confirm that the event handler retrieves and prints the value of the length result.","pos":[11725,11861]},{"content":"If you are new to asynchronous programming, take a minute to consider the difference between synchronous and asynchronous behavior.","pos":[11866,11997]},{"content":"A synchronous method returns when its work is complete (step 5), but an async method returns a task value when its work is suspended (steps 3 and 6).","pos":[11998,12147]},{"content":"When the async method eventually completes its work, the task is marked as completed and the result, if any, is stored in the task.","pos":[12148,12279]},{"pos":[12285,12455],"content":"For more information about control flow, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Control Flow in Async Programs (C#)<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../csharp/programming-guide/concepts/async/control-flow-in-async-programs.md)</ept>.","source":"For more information about control flow, see [Control Flow in Async Programs (C#)](../../../../csharp/programming-guide/concepts/async/control-flow-in-async-programs.md)."},{"pos":[12464,12517],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_APIAsyncMethods\"&gt;</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">&lt;/a&gt;</ept> API async methods","linkify":"<a name=\"BKMK_APIAsyncMethods\"></a> API async methods","source":"<a name=\"BKMK_APIAsyncMethods\"></a> API async methods"},{"content":"You might be wondering where to find methods such as <ph id=\"ph1\">`GetStringAsync`</ph> that support async programming.","pos":[12521,12622],"source":"You might be wondering where to find methods such as `GetStringAsync` that support async programming."},{"content":"The  .NET Framework 4.5 or higher and .NET Core contain many members that work with <ph id=\"ph1\">`async`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`await`</ph>.","pos":[12623,12727],"source":" The  .NET Framework 4.5 or higher and .NET Core contain many members that work with `async` and `await`."},{"content":"You can recognize them by the \"Async\" suffix that’s appended to the member name, and by their return type of <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task&gt;</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601&gt;</ph>.","pos":[12728,12914],"source":" You can recognize them by the \"Async\" suffix that’s appended to the member name, and by their return type of <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task> or <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601>."},{"content":"For example, the <ph id=\"ph1\">`System.IO.Stream`</ph> class contains methods such as <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.IO.Stream.CopyToAsync%2A&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.IO.Stream.ReadAsync%2A&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.IO.Stream.WriteAsync%2A&gt;</ph> alongside the synchronous methods <ph id=\"ph5\">&lt;xref:System.IO.Stream.CopyTo%2A&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph6\">&lt;xref:System.IO.Stream.Read%2A&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph7\">&lt;xref:System.IO.Stream.Write%2A&gt;</ph>.","pos":[12915,13241],"source":" For example, the `System.IO.Stream` class contains methods such as <xref:System.IO.Stream.CopyToAsync%2A>, <xref:System.IO.Stream.ReadAsync%2A>, and <xref:System.IO.Stream.WriteAsync%2A> alongside the synchronous methods <xref:System.IO.Stream.CopyTo%2A>, <xref:System.IO.Stream.Read%2A>, and <xref:System.IO.Stream.Write%2A>."},{"content":"The Windows Runtime also contains many methods that you can use with <ph id=\"ph1\">`async`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`await`</ph> in Windows apps.","pos":[13248,13353],"source":"The Windows Runtime also contains many methods that you can use with `async` and `await` in Windows apps."},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Threading and async programming<ept id=\"p1\">](/windows/uwp/threading-async/)</ept> for UWP development, and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Asynchronous programming (Windows Store apps)<ept id=\"p2\">](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh464924(v=win.10))</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Quickstart: Calling asynchronous APIs in C# or Visual Basic<ept id=\"p3\">](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh452713(v=win.10))</ept> if you use earlier versions of the Windows Runtime.","pos":[13354,13791],"source":" For more information, see [Threading and async programming](/windows/uwp/threading-async/) for UWP development, and [Asynchronous programming (Windows Store apps)](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh464924(v=win.10)) and [Quickstart: Calling asynchronous APIs in C# or Visual Basic](https://docs.microsoft.com/previous-versions/windows/apps/hh452713(v=win.10)) if you use earlier versions of the Windows Runtime."},{"pos":[13800,13835],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_Threads\"&gt;</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">&lt;/a&gt;</ept> Threads","linkify":"<a name=\"BKMK_Threads\"></a> Threads","source":"<a name=\"BKMK_Threads\"></a> Threads"},{"content":"Async methods are intended to be non-blocking operations.","pos":[13838,13895]},{"content":"An <ph id=\"ph1\">`await`</ph> expression in an async method doesn’t block the current thread while the awaited task is running.","pos":[13896,14004],"source":" An `await` expression in an async method doesn’t block the current thread while the awaited task is running."},{"content":"Instead, the expression signs up the rest of the method as a continuation and returns control to the caller of the async method.","pos":[14005,14133]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`async`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`await`</ph> keywords don't cause additional threads to be created.","pos":[14139,14217],"source":"The `async` and `await` keywords don't cause additional threads to be created."},{"content":"Async methods don't require multithreading because an async method doesn't run on its own thread.","pos":[14218,14315]},{"content":"The method runs on the current synchronization context and uses time on the thread only when the method is active.","pos":[14316,14430]},{"content":"You can use <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task.Run%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> to move CPU-bound work to a background thread, but a background thread doesn't help with a process that's just waiting for results to become available.","pos":[14431,14665],"source":" You can use <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task.Run%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> to move CPU-bound work to a background thread, but a background thread doesn't help with a process that's just waiting for results to become available."},{"content":"The async-based approach to asynchronous programming is preferable to existing approaches in almost every case.","pos":[14671,14782]},{"content":"In particular, this approach is better than the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.ComponentModel.BackgroundWorker&gt;</ph> class for I/O-bound operations because the code is simpler and you don't have to guard against race conditions.","pos":[14783,14988],"source":" In particular, this approach is better than the <xref:System.ComponentModel.BackgroundWorker> class for I/O-bound operations because the code is simpler and you don't have to guard against race conditions."},{"content":"In combination with the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task.Run%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method, async programming is better than <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.ComponentModel.BackgroundWorker&gt;</ph> for CPU-bound operations because async programming separates the coordination details of running your code from the work that <ph id=\"ph3\">`Task.Run`</ph> transfers to the threadpool.","pos":[14989,15336],"source":" In combination with the <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task.Run%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method, async programming is better than <xref:System.ComponentModel.BackgroundWorker> for CPU-bound operations because async programming separates the coordination details of running your code from the work that `Task.Run` transfers to the threadpool."},{"pos":[15345,15394],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_AsyncandAwait\"&gt;</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">&lt;/a&gt;</ept> async and await","linkify":"<a name=\"BKMK_AsyncandAwait\"></a> async and await","source":"<a name=\"BKMK_AsyncandAwait\"></a> async and await"},{"pos":[15398,15576],"content":"If you specify that a method is an async method by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>async<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/async.md)</ept> modifier, you enable the following two capabilities.","source":"If you specify that a method is an async method by using the [async](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/async.md) modifier, you enable the following two capabilities."},{"content":"The marked async method can use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>await<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/await.md)</ept> to designate suspension points.","pos":[15586,15714],"source":"The marked async method can use [await](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/await.md) to designate suspension points."},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`await`</ph> operator tells the compiler that the async method can't continue past that point until the awaited asynchronous process is complete.","pos":[15715,15859],"source":" The `await` operator tells the compiler that the async method can't continue past that point until the awaited asynchronous process is complete."},{"content":"In the meantime, control returns to the caller of the async method.","pos":[15860,15927]},{"pos":[15938,16072],"content":"The suspension of an async method at an <ph id=\"ph1\">`await`</ph> expression doesn't constitute an exit from the method, and <ph id=\"ph2\">`finally`</ph> blocks don’t run.","source":"The suspension of an async method at an `await` expression doesn't constitute an exit from the method, and `finally` blocks don’t run."},{"content":"The marked async method can itself be awaited by methods that call it.","pos":[16082,16152]},{"content":"An async method typically contains one or more occurrences of an <ph id=\"ph1\">`await`</ph> operator, but the absence of <ph id=\"ph2\">`await`</ph> expressions doesn’t cause a compiler error.","pos":[16158,16311],"source":"An async method typically contains one or more occurrences of an `await` operator, but the absence of `await` expressions doesn’t cause a compiler error."},{"content":"If an async method doesn’t use an <ph id=\"ph1\">`await`</ph> operator to mark a suspension point, the method executes as a synchronous method does, despite the <ph id=\"ph2\">`async`</ph> modifier.","pos":[16312,16470],"source":" If an async method doesn’t use an `await` operator to mark a suspension point, the method executes as a synchronous method does, despite the `async` modifier."},{"content":"The compiler issues a warning for such methods.","pos":[16471,16518]},{"content":"<ph id=\"ph1\">`async`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`await`</ph> are contextual keywords.","pos":[16525,16569],"source":"`async` and `await` are contextual keywords."},{"content":"For more information and examples, see the following topics:","pos":[16570,16630]},{"pos":[16640,16704],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>async<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/async.md)</ept>","source":"[async](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/async.md)"},{"pos":[16714,16778],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>await<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/await.md)</ept>","source":"[await](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/await.md)"},{"pos":[16787,16859],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_ReturnTypesandParameters\"&gt;</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">&lt;/a&gt;</ept> Return types and parameters","linkify":"<a name=\"BKMK_ReturnTypesandParameters\"></a> Return types and parameters","source":"<a name=\"BKMK_ReturnTypesandParameters\"></a> Return types and parameters"},{"content":"An async method typically returns a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task&gt;</ph> or a <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601&gt;</ph>.","pos":[16862,16977],"source":"An async method typically returns a <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task> or a <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601>."},{"content":"Inside an async method, an <ph id=\"ph1\">`await`</ph> operator is applied to a task that's returned from a call to another async method.","pos":[16978,17095],"source":" Inside an async method, an `await` operator is applied to a task that's returned from a call to another async method."},{"pos":[17101,17319],"content":"You specify <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601&gt;</ph> as the return type if the method contains a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ph id=\"ph2\">`return`</ph><ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../csharp/language-reference/keywords/return.md)</ept> statement that specifies an operand of type <ph id=\"ph3\">`TResult`</ph>.","source":"You specify <xref:System.Threading.Tasks.Task%601> as the return type if the method contains a [`r